{"id":"astro-ph/0604308","submitter":"Robyn Levine","authors":"Robyn Levine and Nickolay Y. Gnedin","title":"AGN Outflows and the Matter Power Spectrum","comments":"submitted to ApJL","journal-ref":"Astrophys.J.649:L57-L60,2006","doi":"10.1086/508370","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We have investigated the effects of AGN outflows on the amplitude of the\nmatter power spectrum in a simple model of spherically symmetric outflows\naround realistically clustered AGN population. We find that two competing\neffects influence the matter power spectrum in two opposite directions. First,\nAGN outflows move baryons from high to low density regions, decreasing the\namplitude of the matter power spectrum by up to 20%. Second, high clustering of\nthe AGN transfers the power from small to larger scales. The exact balance\nbetween these two effects depends on the details of outflows on small scales,\nand quantitative estimates will require much more sophisticated modeling than\npresented here.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 13 Apr 2006 16:59:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-02-11"}
